# .gitignore — PATCHED
#
# Rename to `.gitignore` when applying.
#
# S-17: the original contained a single hardcoded line:
#
#     AuthKey_P5P4S37T4B.p8
#
# That discloses the App Store Connect API Key ID `P5P4S37T4B` permanently
# in version control. The ID alone is not a credential — authenticating
# needs the .p8 private key and the issuer ID as well — so this is
# information disclosure rather than a breach. But its presence means the
# .p8 was sitting in the working tree at some point, which is exactly how
# private keys get committed by accident.
#
# BEFORE TRUSTING THIS FILE, run against the real repository:
#
#     git log --all --full-history -- '*.p8' '*.p12' '*.mobileprovision'
#     git log -p --all -S 'BEGIN PRIVATE KEY'
#
# If anything turns up, revoke that key in App Store Connect immediately.
# Rewriting history is not sufficient once a key has been pushed — assume
# any commit that ever reached a remote has been cloned.

# ---- Build output -----------------------------------------------------
.DS_Store
DerivedData/
.build/
build/
*.xcuserstate
xcuserdata/
.swiftpm/

# XcodeGen generates this from project.yml; committing it causes merge
# conflicts and lets hand-edits silently diverge from the manifest.
*.xcodeproj/

# ---- Signing material and credentials (S-17) --------------------------
# Patterns, never specific filenames — a filename in .gitignore leaks the
# identifier it is meant to protect.
*.p8
*.p12
*.pem
*.key
*.cer
*.certSigningRequest
*.mobileprovision
*.provisionprofile
ExportOptions.plist

# ---- Local environment ------------------------------------------------
.env
.env.*
*.local.xcconfig

# ---- Models -----------------------------------------------------------
# Multi-hundred-MB GGML/GGUF weights do not belong in git. Fetch them in
# CI or ship them via a release asset / LFS.
*.gguf
*.bin
*.mlmodelc/
OffGrid/Resources/Models/
